programme.title: Sheffield United v Bradford City
programme.desc: Second play fourth in this fixture – a fixture that, on the face of it, looks a tough one to call, at least in terms of a winner. Having lost just once each in their last five matches, both teams have been in pretty good form and, in all honesty, this one could easily swing either way(c)

programme.title: Fulham v Aston Villa
programme.desc: Villa picked up their first win under Steve Bruce and their first on the road in over a year on Tuesday night with a 2-1 win at Reading. A late Jordan Ayew penalty sealed the 3 points and could just prove a turning point in their season. There can be little doubt there is enough quality in the Villa squad to compete for promotion this season but confidence has been very low at Villa Park for some time so they’ll be desperate to record a second win in five days here. The Claret and Blues haven’t recorded successive victories since winning back-to-back Premier League games against Everton and West Ham late in the 2014-15 season. It has been pretty much downhill ever since and one victory alone is unlikely to totally resolve all their issues ,so the nervous defending and goalkeeping that has been a feature of their season could still be evident on Saturday which gives hope to Fulham(c)

programme.title: Football today
programme.desc: Brought to you By Renegades(c)

programme.title: Derby County v Huddersfield Town
programme.desc: Derby have made a mixed start to life under Darren Wassall. They lost their first game under the new man going down surprisingly 1-0 at home to MK Dons before bouncing back with successive wins over Brentford and Blackburn. However they were beaten 2-1 at Wolves last time out and come into the game in 5th place with the gap between them and the top two in danger of reaching the point where their automatic promotion dreams are as good as over. This is almost certainly a must-win game for the Rams if they are to maintain hopes of a top two finish. Huddersfield’s form has been a bit patchy. They’ve won just 2 of their last 8 matches suffering 5 defeats although one of those wins was an impressive 2-0 victory at Nottingham Forest. They were beaten 1-0 at home to Ipswich last weekend though but with a 10 point lead on the bottom three they don’t have too much to worry about(c)

programme.title: Football today
programme.desc: Brought to you By Renegades(c)

programme.title: Middlesbrough v Arsenal
programme.desc: Arsenal will certainly not want another meek Monday night after their sorry showing at Selhurst Park. Last week their team coach was delayed in traffic in south London, but I remember 10 years ago the Arsenal bus, en route to the Riverside, took a wrong turn and started heading towards Darlington. They lost 2-1 to Middlesbrough that day. Critics of Arsene Wenger will say the club is lacking direction. The statistics certainly reinforce those that think Arsenal have lost their way - they've won seven points out of a possible 24 since the end of January. Sam Allardyce tactically exposed Arsenal but can Steve Agnew follow suit? A winning formula is essential because time is running out for Boro, who have scored the fewest home goals of any side in the top four divisions in England(c)
